.TH "CanvasRenderingContext2D.beginPath" "JS" "July 26, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
CanvasRenderingContext2D.beginPath \- CanvasRenderingContext2D:
beginPath() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]CanvasRenderingContext2D.beginPath()\f[B]\f[R] method of
the Canvas 2D API starts a new path by emptying the list of sub\-paths.
Call this method when you want to create a new path.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] To create a new sub\-path, i.e., one matching the
current canvas state, you can use
\f[CR]CanvasRenderingContext2D.moveTo()\f[R].
.RE
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
beginPath()
.EE
.SS Parameters
None.
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Creating distinct paths
This example creates two paths, each of which contains a single line.
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]canvas\f[R] id=\[dq]canvas\[dq]></\f[B]canvas\f[R]>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
The \f[CR]beginPath()\f[R] method is called before beginning each line,
so that they may be drawn with different colors.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] canvas = document.getElementById(\[dq]canvas\[dq]);
\f[B]const\f[R] ctx = canvas.getContext(\[dq]2d\[dq]);

\f[I]// First path\f[R]
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.strokeStyle = \[dq]blue\[dq];
ctx.moveTo(20, 20);
ctx.lineTo(200, 20);
ctx.stroke();

\f[I]// Second path\f[R]
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.strokeStyle = \[dq]green\[dq];
ctx.moveTo(20, 20);
ctx.lineTo(120, 120);
ctx.stroke();
.EE
